WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.800 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:02.780 align:middle line:90%
>> This is "Nuevo."

00:00:02.780 --> 00:00:07.840 align:middle line:84%
After 44 years, the United
States Space Agency NASA

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:10.460 align:middle line:84%
will return to look
for life on Mars.

00:00:10.460 --> 00:00:17.420 align:middle line:84%
In 1976, a team of scientist led
by NASA engineer Gilbert Levin

00:00:17.420 --> 00:00:21.030 align:middle line:84%
claimed to have found
life on the Red Planet.

00:00:21.030 --> 00:00:24.170 align:middle line:84%
However, the directors
of the Viking mission

00:00:24.170 --> 00:00:28.190 align:middle line:84%
did not reach a consensus
on whether his results were

00:00:28.190 --> 00:00:29.780 align:middle line:90%
proof of life.

00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:34.280 align:middle line:84%
Since then, there have been
no future searches for life

00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:35.150 align:middle line:90%
on Mars.

00:00:35.150 --> 00:00:37.700 align:middle line:84%
Though, there have
been exploration

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:40.430 align:middle line:84%
for waters and
continued investigation

00:00:40.430 --> 00:00:43.910 align:middle line:84%
of the geological composition
of the Red Planet.

00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:47.990 align:middle line:84%
There is no clear reason why
the search for life on Mars

00:00:47.990 --> 00:00:49.760 align:middle line:90%
has been avoided.

00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:52.850 align:middle line:84%
The most important
mission for Rover 2020

00:00:52.850 --> 00:00:56.940 align:middle line:84%
will be precisely this,
to look for life on Mars.

00:00:56.940 --> 00:00:57.980 align:middle line:90%
This is Nuevo.

00:00:57.980 --> 00:01:00.415 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:01:00.415 --> 00:01:07.720 align:middle line:90%


00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:16.066 align:middle line:10%
>> Gaia presents "Nuevo"
with Jaime Maussan.

00:01:16.066 --> 00:01:22.070 align:middle line:90%


00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:26.540 align:middle line:10%
>> While the NASA missions are
being organized for a potential

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:30.350 align:middle line:10%
site landing of
the rover in 2020,

00:01:30.350 --> 00:01:35.000 align:middle line:10%
the Russian-European Trace
Gas Orbiter mission is already

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.260 align:middle line:10%
collecting data, which could
soon produce results that good

00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:43.950 align:middle line:10%
lead scientists to confirm
that life does, in fact,

00:01:43.950 --> 00:01:45.837 align:middle line:10%
exist on Mars.

00:01:45.837 --> 00:01:47.210 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:01:47.210 --> 00:01:49.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Since the beginning
of the new millennium,

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:52.670 align:middle line:84%
the European Space Agency
has sought to confirm that

00:01:52.670 --> 00:01:56.690 align:middle line:84%
the presence of methane on
Mars is a result of bacteria

00:01:56.690 --> 00:01:59.450 align:middle line:90%
activity producing this gas.

00:01:59.450 --> 00:02:03.170 align:middle line:84%
The Andalusia Institute
of Astrophysics designed

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:05.240 align:middle line:84%
part of the NOMAD
instruments, which

00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:09.560 align:middle line:84%
are a key piece of the ExoMars
Orbiter specifically intended

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:11.150 align:middle line:90%
to study methane--

00:02:11.150 --> 00:02:13.970 align:middle line:90%
a gas that the Earth produces.

00:02:13.970 --> 00:02:17.390 align:middle line:84%
Living organisms naturally
produce this gas.

00:02:17.390 --> 00:02:23.490 align:middle line:84%
And the discovery on Mars was
a complete surprise in 2004.

00:02:23.490 --> 00:02:27.150 align:middle line:84%
The European Space Agency's
Mars Express Orbiter

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:30.150 align:middle line:84%
found large amounts of
methane at that time

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:31.920 align:middle line:90%
on the surface of Mars.

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:34.650 align:middle line:90%
And then oddly, it disappeared.

00:02:34.650 --> 00:02:38.370 align:middle line:84%
Methane, a natural gas,
takes centuries to degrade.

00:02:38.370 --> 00:02:40.470 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, the
surprising variability

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:43.170 align:middle line:84%
of methane abundance
led some scientists

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:47.220 align:middle line:84%
to suggest its organic
origin and its presence

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:52.440 align:middle line:84%
was cyclical, meaning it is
related to seasonal spikes.

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:55.470 align:middle line:84%
Since then, European scientists
have carried out missions

00:02:55.470 --> 00:02:58.830 align:middle line:84%
to search for bacteria
that produce methane.

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:01.080 align:middle line:84%
But they have been
faced with a planet that

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:02.640 align:middle line:90%
is very unpredictable.

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:07.540 align:middle line:90%


00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:12.010 align:middle line:84%
Both the Beagle mission in 2003
and the Schiaparelli mission

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:15.550 align:middle line:84%
in 2016 succumbed
to a planet that

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:18.520 align:middle line:84%
has become the graveyard
of countless missions

00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:21.710 align:middle line:90%
over the past 50 years.

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:24.310 align:middle line:84%
However, the Trace
Gas Orbiter mission

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:27.860 align:middle line:84%
could generate extraordinary
results in the coming months.

00:03:27.860 --> 00:03:30.370 align:middle line:84%
But only if it was
confirmed that methane

00:03:30.370 --> 00:03:34.510 align:middle line:84%
appears and disappears with
a predictable regularity.

00:03:34.510 --> 00:03:38.080 align:middle line:84%
The Schiaparelli mission could
have confirmed these results

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:41.920 align:middle line:84%
with an analysis on the
ground, but unfortunately, it

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:44.510 align:middle line:90%
did not happen.

00:03:44.510 --> 00:03:48.370 align:middle line:84%
NOMAD will not only generate
the first accurate global map

00:03:48.370 --> 00:03:52.870 align:middle line:84%
of methane in the atmosphere of
Mars, but will also track it.

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:55.690 align:middle line:84%
Observing it against the
surface of the Red Planet

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:57.790 align:middle line:84%
to find the source
of production,

00:03:57.790 --> 00:04:00.580 align:middle line:84%
and the disappearance of
the gas when it happens.

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:03.850 align:middle line:84%
NOMAD will also be able to
distinguish the methane's

00:04:03.850 --> 00:04:07.300 align:middle line:84%
isotopic composition
to find its geological

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:08.860 align:middle line:90%
or biological origin.

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:14.110 align:middle line:90%


00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:16.899 align:middle line:84%
Meanwhile, the
2020 rover mission

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:20.350 align:middle line:84%
is preparing to collect
samples of the Martian soil,

00:04:20.350 --> 00:04:25.130 align:middle line:84%
and send them back to
Earth, not an easy task.

00:04:25.130 --> 00:04:29.980 align:middle line:84%
The general mission is known
as MSR, the Mars Sample Return

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:34.180 align:middle line:84%
mission, and will consist of at
least three separate missions.

00:04:34.180 --> 00:04:38.530 align:middle line:84%
In the first mission, the 2020
Mars, a twin of Curiosity,

00:04:38.530 --> 00:04:41.530 align:middle line:84%
will take a drill and
collect soil samples

00:04:41.530 --> 00:04:43.810 align:middle line:84%
throughout its land
exploration process.

00:04:43.810 --> 00:04:46.470 align:middle line:90%


00:04:46.470 --> 00:04:51.170 align:middle line:84%
The second stage will be the
SRL probe, a sample retrieval

00:04:51.170 --> 00:04:54.170 align:middle line:84%
and launch mission to
collect the samples obtained

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:58.550 align:middle line:84%
by the 2020 Rover, and
launch them into Mars orbit

00:04:58.550 --> 00:05:02.890 align:middle line:84%
to be collected
by the SRO probes.

00:05:02.890 --> 00:05:06.100 align:middle line:84%
The probe will be launched
into space by a MAV--

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.180 align:middle line:90%
a Mars ascent vehicle.

00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:10.930 align:middle line:84%
This is a rover based
on the Curiosity design

00:05:10.930 --> 00:05:15.740 align:middle line:84%
that would transport the
MAV rocket on its back.

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:18.010 align:middle line:84%
This mobile MAV would
be able to travel over

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:21.010 align:middle line:84%
a considerable distance,
and could launch the MAV

00:05:21.010 --> 00:05:23.170 align:middle line:84%
from almost any
point in its journey.

00:05:23.170 --> 00:05:26.850 align:middle line:90%


00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:30.540 align:middle line:84%
The orbiter that will transport
the samples back to Earth

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:33.270 align:middle line:90%
will be launched in 2024.

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:36.360 align:middle line:84%
And it is thought that before
the end of the next decade,

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:40.320 align:middle line:84%
it will be possible to confirm
or reject the possibility

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:43.535 align:middle line:84%
that microscopic life
on Mars now exists.

00:05:43.535 --> 00:05:49.110 align:middle line:90%


00:05:49.110 --> 00:05:53.220 align:middle line:84%
According to the plans, NASA
has three possible scenarios

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:55.800 align:middle line:90%
to search for life on Mars.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:59.190 align:middle line:84%
The Jezero crater, a
favorite among researchers,

00:05:59.190 --> 00:06:01.320 align:middle line:84%
is an ancient lake
with sediments

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:04.350 align:middle line:90%
of all types and fossil deltas.

00:06:04.350 --> 00:06:07.170 align:middle line:84%
The presence of carbonates
and phyllosilicates

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:09.960 align:middle line:84%
indicate that the water
of the lake at one time

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:15.160 align:middle line:84%
had a neutral pH, meaning that
it was habitable for life.

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:18.930 align:middle line:84%
Unlike other younger areas on
Mars, such as the Meridiani

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:21.510 align:middle line:84%
Planum, the second
place, selected

00:06:21.510 --> 00:06:25.890 align:middle line:84%
is the region of Syrtis Major,
one of the oldest on Mars.

00:06:25.890 --> 00:06:27.900 align:middle line:84%
And is covered by
clay minerals that

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:33.300 align:middle line:84%
revealed the ancient presence
of water at high temperatures.

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:36.300 align:middle line:84%
In this location, the
area of Columbia Hills,

00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:39.150 align:middle line:84%
the Gusev crater is
already well-known

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:43.440 align:middle line:84%
as it was explored by the famous
Spirit rover a decade ago.

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:45.960 align:middle line:84%
Its inclusion in the list
of possible candidate

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:48.930 align:middle line:84%
locations for Mars
2020 exploration

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:51.450 align:middle line:90%
has caused much controversy.

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:54.600 align:middle line:84%
The discovery of the
presence of silica by Spirit

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:56.640 align:middle line:84%
is evidence that
in the past, there

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:01.260 align:middle line:84%
were hydrothermal vents
in the surface of Mars.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:05.910 align:middle line:84%
Syrtis Major, or Jezero, are
areas in which liquid water

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:08.760 align:middle line:90%
ran across the Martian surface.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:12.540 align:middle line:84%
In Columbia Hills, the water
came out of its interior.

00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:15.300 align:middle line:84%
If this place is chosen,
it would be the first time

00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:18.300 align:middle line:84%
that a Martian probe has
landed in the same place

00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:20.310 align:middle line:90%
as a previous mission.

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:23.490 align:middle line:84%
However, of the three
places, Columbia Hills

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:25.290 align:middle line:90%
was the least preferred.

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:28.290 align:middle line:84%
And few believe that they will
be in the final selection.

00:07:28.290 --> 00:07:35.715 align:middle line:90%


00:07:35.715 --> 00:07:38.190 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:39.180 align:middle line:90%


00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:42.810 align:middle line:84%
>> In short, the existence
of methane on Mars is one

00:07:42.810 --> 00:07:46.360 align:middle line:84%
of the great mysteries
of the Red Planet.

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:48.600 align:middle line:84%
Making a categorical
conclusion will take

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:50.850 align:middle line:90%
many more years of research.

00:07:50.850 --> 00:07:53.280 align:middle line:84%
Only then, will it
be possible to know

00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:56.476 align:middle line:90%
if life ever existed on Mars.

00:07:56.476 --> 00:07:58.956 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:58.956 --> 00:08:02.930 align:middle line:90%


00:08:02.930 --> 00:08:07.560 align:middle line:84%
>> In 1976, two different
missions landed on Mars.

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:13.850 align:middle line:84%
And then in May of 1977, Viking
twin probes descended to Mars.

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:17.000 align:middle line:84%
Those responsible for the
Viking Martian Exploration

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.600 align:middle line:84%
Program found evidence
of biological properties

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:25.530 align:middle line:84%
in the analysis of the soil and
atmosphere of the Red Planet.

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:28.640 align:middle line:10%
The probes, which reached
their destination respectively

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:33.470 align:middle line:10%
in July and September
of 1976, were expressly

00:08:33.470 --> 00:08:37.280 align:middle line:10%
equipped for a series of
specific organic tests.

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:40.940 align:middle line:84%
Among them was one aimed
at analyzing the atmosphere

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:44.120 align:middle line:84%
in search of gases
of biological origin

00:08:44.120 --> 00:08:47.570 align:middle line:84%
that existed in
significant quantities.

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:49.470 align:middle line:84%
The soil study,
on the other hand,

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:53.300 align:middle line:84%
was carried out through
four biochemical tests.

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:56.420 align:middle line:84%
After months of studying
the data that was obtained,

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:59.060 align:middle line:84%
the official NASA
conclusions stated

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:01.730 align:middle line:90%
that there was no life on Mars.

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:04.550 align:middle line:84%
But there are still
other conflicting voices.

00:09:04.550 --> 00:09:08.420 align:middle line:10%
In 2016, Gilbert Levin,
who is responsible for one

00:09:08.420 --> 00:09:11.450 align:middle line:10%
of the experiments carried
out by the Viking probes,

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:13.970 align:middle line:10%
published an article
in the magazine

00:09:13.970 --> 00:09:18.710 align:middle line:10%
"Astrobiology," in cooperation
with biologist Patricia Straat.

00:09:18.710 --> 00:09:22.400 align:middle line:84%
In it, he defends what he
has claimed, and I quote,

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:24.470 align:middle line:84%
"the experimental
tests of the Viking

00:09:24.470 --> 00:09:26.990 align:middle line:84%
indicate that on the
surface of the Red Planet,

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:30.200 align:middle line:84%
there are microorganisms
capable of surviving

00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:33.800 align:middle line:84%
in the harsh conditions of
the Martian environment."

00:09:33.800 --> 00:09:37.100 align:middle line:84%
Life on Mars is an idea
that only a small group

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:38.300 align:middle line:90%
of scientists share.

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:41.690 align:middle line:90%


00:09:41.690 --> 00:09:46.760 align:middle line:84%
>> I was able to put together
an experiment that went to Mars

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:52.640 align:middle line:84%
to look for life, by picking up
a sample of the Martian soil--

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:56.720 align:middle line:84%
the Viking spacecraft
Lander did that.

00:09:56.720 --> 00:10:01.850 align:middle line:84%
And inoculating it
into a small tube,

00:10:01.850 --> 00:10:07.850 align:middle line:84%
in which a squirt of
radioactive nutrient was placed.

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:10.640 align:middle line:84%
Were any microorganisms
present--

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:14.450 align:middle line:84%
hopefully-- they would
recognize the nutrient,

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:18.050 align:middle line:84%
eat it, and give
off radioactive gas.

00:10:18.050 --> 00:10:22.880 align:middle line:84%
Well, no one, including
me, was very hopeful this

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:25.130 align:middle line:90%
would work on Mars.

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:28.940 align:middle line:84%
However, the possibility
of life on Mars

00:10:28.940 --> 00:10:33.800 align:middle line:84%
was so astounding that NASA
described the whole experiment

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:37.460 align:middle line:84%
of looking for life on Mars
as perhaps, the greatest

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:40.460 align:middle line:84%
experiment in the
history of science.

00:10:40.460 --> 00:10:41.900 align:middle line:90%
Which is puzzling.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:44.250 align:middle line:84%
Because while they
still say that,

00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:49.280 align:middle line:84%
there's something wrong in
their lack of pursuit of it.

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:52.400 align:middle line:84%
At any rate,
surprisingly, as soon

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:56.420 align:middle line:84%
as the first square squirt of
nutrient hit that Martian soil,

00:10:56.420 --> 00:11:00.080 align:middle line:84%
we got a big bulge
of gas coming out.

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:06.590 align:middle line:84%
And it came out for the entire
seven days, or Martian sols,

00:11:06.590 --> 00:11:09.200 align:middle line:90%
of the experiment.

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:11.000 align:middle line:90%
That was astounding.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.740 align:middle line:10%
But we had conceived
of that possibility

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:20.270 align:middle line:10%
being false, being
absolutely conducted

00:11:20.270 --> 00:11:24.030 align:middle line:10%
by chemicals in the soil,
rather than microorganisms.

00:11:24.030 --> 00:11:26.450 align:middle line:90%
So we had a test for that, too.

00:11:26.450 --> 00:11:30.140 align:middle line:84%
We had a control experiment
carefully designed,

00:11:30.140 --> 00:11:32.390 align:middle line:90%
really designed by NASA.

00:11:32.390 --> 00:11:38.070 align:middle line:84%
And it was if you ever unlikely
got a positive response,

00:11:38.070 --> 00:11:42.260 align:middle line:84%
you would take a duplicate
sample of that same soil.

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:47.720 align:middle line:84%
And put it in a little tube,
just like the first sample.

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:52.430 align:middle line:84%
But now heated to 160 degrees
centigrade-- a temperature

00:11:52.430 --> 00:11:57.560 align:middle line:84%
they selected as killing any
microorganisms known on Earth,

00:11:57.560 --> 00:12:02.840 align:middle line:84%
but not high enough to
destroy oxidizing chemicals

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:05.330 align:middle line:84%
that might have
given a false answer.

00:12:05.330 --> 00:12:07.550 align:middle line:90%
So this is called the control.

00:12:07.550 --> 00:12:09.530 align:middle line:90%
You run the control.

00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:15.110 align:middle line:84%
And if it's positive, then
the agent that was active,

00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:18.440 align:middle line:84%
survived the heating-- so it's
not microbial, it's chemical.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:20.900 align:middle line:84%
But if it's negative,
you've killed

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:23.190 align:middle line:90%
something that had been alive.

00:12:23.190 --> 00:12:26.390 align:middle line:84%
And that's the confirmation
that it was indeed,

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:29.810 align:middle line:84%
a positive response for
living microorganisms

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:32.150 align:middle line:90%
in the soil of Mars.

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:33.880 align:middle line:90%
That is what happened.

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:36.135 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:12:36.135 --> 00:12:38.390 align:middle line:90%


00:12:38.390 --> 00:12:41.870 align:middle line:84%
>> The Viking experiments were
designed to look for life forms

00:12:41.870 --> 00:12:45.480 align:middle line:84%
using the knowledge
of the '60s and '70s.

00:12:45.480 --> 00:12:48.680 align:middle line:84%
But it was not until the
early '80s when a type

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:52.490 align:middle line:84%
of microorganism that could live
in such unfriendly conditions

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:54.290 align:middle line:90%
was discovered--

00:12:54.290 --> 00:12:57.350 align:middle line:90%
extremophiles.

00:12:57.350 --> 00:13:00.800 align:middle line:84%
So we may simply not be
looking for the right organisms

00:13:00.800 --> 00:13:02.120 align:middle line:90%
on Mars.

00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:04.700 align:middle line:84%
According to Gilbert Levin,
one of the experiments

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:07.820 align:middle line:84%
showed that the soil
of Mars did indeed,

00:13:07.820 --> 00:13:12.380 align:middle line:84%
test positive for a
metabolism or microorganism.

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:16.910 align:middle line:84%
A sign that on Earth, would
suggest the presence of life.

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:25.740 align:middle line:84%
>> For the 37 intervening years,
NASA and other astrobiology

00:13:25.740 --> 00:13:30.540 align:middle line:84%
scientists have been explaining
away or attempting to explain

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:35.340 align:middle line:84%
away the Labeled Release,
my experimental results.

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:37.050 align:middle line:90%
They've been unsuccessful.

00:13:37.050 --> 00:13:41.970 align:middle line:84%
No one has ever reproduced
in the laboratory

00:13:41.970 --> 00:13:46.650 align:middle line:84%
or even in theory, a chemical
that will react in that manner

00:13:46.650 --> 00:13:49.830 align:middle line:90%
and give those control results.

00:13:49.830 --> 00:13:51.870 align:middle line:90%
But it did not bother them.

00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:55.440 align:middle line:84%
They still contend that
it's some weird chemical.

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:57.270 align:middle line:84%
One of them even
said perhaps, it's

00:13:57.270 --> 00:13:59.370 align:middle line:90%
chemistry turning into biology.

00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:04.190 align:middle line:10%
We may have arrived at
Mars at an historic time.

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:09.140 align:middle line:84%
Well, since then, we've learned
so much about life on Earth--

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:12.170 align:middle line:84%
that it exists every
place, except perhaps,

00:14:12.170 --> 00:14:14.990 align:middle line:90%
in red hot lava.

00:14:14.990 --> 00:14:17.990 align:middle line:84%
But wherever you go--
up, down, sideways--

00:14:17.990 --> 00:14:22.430 align:middle line:84%
there's something alive under
conditions that are sometimes

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:24.650 align:middle line:90%
as bad as any on Mars.

00:14:24.650 --> 00:14:28.550 align:middle line:84%
And yet, these bugs
thrive on Earth.

00:14:28.550 --> 00:14:32.030 align:middle line:84%
Since my experiment,
NASA has refused

00:14:32.030 --> 00:14:35.180 align:middle line:84%
to send another life
detection experiment

00:14:35.180 --> 00:14:38.510 align:middle line:90%
to Mars or any place.

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:41.600 align:middle line:84%
Every time I have
sent in an upgrade

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:46.550 align:middle line:84%
of my original experiment as a
proposal for a new spacecraft,

00:14:46.550 --> 00:14:48.060 align:middle line:90%
it's been rejected.

00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:51.050 align:middle line:84%
I was told directly by the
head of the Mars program,

00:14:51.050 --> 00:14:55.820 align:middle line:84%
if you send in another
proposal to send an experiment

00:14:55.820 --> 00:14:58.700 align:middle line:84%
to look for life on Mars, it
will be immediately rejected.

00:14:58.700 --> 00:15:00.900 align:middle line:90%
That's bad science.

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:03.680 align:middle line:84%
The reason they give
is because if they

00:15:03.680 --> 00:15:05.960 align:middle line:90%
got another equivocal answer--

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:09.530 align:middle line:84%
which they now admit, we're
not sure it wasn't life,

00:15:09.530 --> 00:15:11.965 align:middle line:90%
but it's at least ambiguous--

00:15:11.965 --> 00:15:13.740 align:middle line:84%
if we got another
ambiguous answer,

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:16.640 align:middle line:84%
it would hurt our
program drastically.

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:18.590 align:middle line:84%
So we're not going
to take a chance.

00:15:18.590 --> 00:15:21.545 align:middle line:84%
That is not science,
that is politics.

00:15:21.545 --> 00:15:23.000 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.940 align:middle line:84%
>> Levin concluded that
the experiment had actually

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:28.160 align:middle line:90%
detected life on Mars.

00:15:28.160 --> 00:15:31.370 align:middle line:84%
And he has championed
that viewpoint ever since.

00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:33.500 align:middle line:84%
The instrument got
positive responses

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:35.540 align:middle line:90%
at both landing locales.

00:15:35.540 --> 00:15:38.120 align:middle line:84%
However, scientists did
not reach a consensus

00:15:38.120 --> 00:15:41.460 align:middle line:84%
on whether his results
were proof of life.

00:15:41.460 --> 00:15:44.120 align:middle line:84%
We know now that with
our present technology,

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:46.400 align:middle line:84%
it is logical that
scientists would not

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:50.360 align:middle line:84%
have found life or
traces of water in 1976.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:53.390 align:middle line:84%
The Viking probes were
unable to detect water,

00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:56.660 align:middle line:84%
but found sediments that
showed high levels of iron that

00:15:56.660 --> 00:16:00.620 align:middle line:84%
would have oxidized the organic
compounds to carbon dioxide,

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:04.070 align:middle line:84%
going unnoticed by the
NASA mission teams.

00:16:04.070 --> 00:16:05.930 align:middle line:84%
The probes analytical
Instruments

00:16:05.930 --> 00:16:09.150 align:middle line:84%
did detect the presence
of carbon dioxide,

00:16:09.150 --> 00:16:12.500 align:middle line:84%
but it was attributed to
an atmospheric or inorganic

00:16:12.500 --> 00:16:15.040 align:middle line:90%
source.

00:16:15.040 --> 00:16:17.260 align:middle line:84%
>> Now, in the
intervening years,

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:20.560 align:middle line:84%
several experimenters have
demonstrated there was

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:24.070 align:middle line:84%
something wrong with the
instrument that went to look

00:16:24.070 --> 00:16:26.410 align:middle line:90%
for organic matter on Mars.

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:30.940 align:middle line:84%
And they have explained it
away, they had impugned it.

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:36.730 align:middle line:10%
None of the original
complaints against the validity

00:16:36.730 --> 00:16:38.570 align:middle line:10%
of the Labeled
Release experiment

00:16:38.570 --> 00:16:42.580 align:middle line:10%
remained, except the
general statement,

00:16:42.580 --> 00:16:45.820 align:middle line:10%
it's the consensus
of astrobiologists

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:49.110 align:middle line:10%
that life was not detected.

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:52.870 align:middle line:10%
Now, science doesn't
work by consensus.

00:16:52.870 --> 00:16:56.500 align:middle line:10%
As a matter of fact, when
Jim Martin set our Viking

00:16:56.500 --> 00:16:59.890 align:middle line:10%
1 down on the ground, he
had delayed putting it down

00:16:59.890 --> 00:17:04.420 align:middle line:10%
for two orbits because he had
seen these rocks on the ground.

00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:07.569 align:middle line:84%
He took a vote of the
scientists assembled there--

00:17:07.569 --> 00:17:09.069 align:middle line:90%
17 of us.

00:17:09.069 --> 00:17:11.895 align:middle line:90%
All 17 said, let's go down.

00:17:11.895 --> 00:17:14.180 align:middle line:90%
We're going to run out of time.

00:17:14.180 --> 00:17:16.510 align:middle line:84%
And he says, well,
thanks for your opinion.

00:17:16.510 --> 00:17:18.970 align:middle line:84%
Science is not a
democratic process.

00:17:18.970 --> 00:17:20.650 align:middle line:90%
We are not going down.

00:17:20.650 --> 00:17:24.640 align:middle line:84%
And he went one more orbit,
and got us down safely.

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:28.150 align:middle line:84%
What I'm trying to do
is get us down safely

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:33.260 align:middle line:84%
to rid us of the paradigm
that we are alone.

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:34.820 align:middle line:90%
We are not alone.

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:37.270 align:middle line:90%
There is life on Mars.

00:17:37.270 --> 00:17:42.190 align:middle line:84%
And that means there should
be life throughout the cosmos.

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:48.250 align:middle line:10%
The next experiment should be to
send up that chiral experiment

00:17:48.250 --> 00:17:52.240 align:middle line:10%
to see whether life on
Mars is the same as life

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:54.310 align:middle line:10%
on Earth or different.

00:17:54.310 --> 00:17:56.890 align:middle line:84%
If the chirality
were different, that

00:17:56.890 --> 00:17:58.840 align:middle line:90%
would be a stupendous discovery.

00:17:58.840 --> 00:18:02.776 align:middle line:84%
It would open up
the cosmos to life.

00:18:02.776 --> 00:18:05.256 align:middle line:10%
