00:18:05.256 --> 00:18:06.250 align:middle line:90%


00:18:06.250 --> 00:18:11.040 align:middle line:84%
>> On August 4, 2007, the
Phoenix mission was sent

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:12.270 align:middle line:90%
to Mars.

00:18:12.270 --> 00:18:15.810 align:middle line:84%
Its main objective was
to determine if there was

00:18:15.810 --> 00:18:18.300 align:middle line:90%
water under the soil of Mars.

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:21.510 align:middle line:84%
And to determine the
characteristics of the soil

00:18:21.510 --> 00:18:25.620 align:middle line:84%
to establish its viability
for the development of plant

00:18:25.620 --> 00:18:28.488 align:middle line:90%
life on this extreme planet.

00:18:28.488 --> 00:18:30.480 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:35.040 align:middle line:10%
>> On June 19, 2008, NASA
claimed that the Phoenix probe

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:38.970 align:middle line:10%
had found ice when performing an
excavation near the north pole

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:40.350 align:middle line:10%
of Mars.

00:18:40.350 --> 00:18:43.020 align:middle line:84%
Earlier, some pieces
of ice were classified

00:18:43.020 --> 00:18:46.860 align:middle line:84%
after being unearthed on
June 15 by the mechanical arm

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:48.330 align:middle line:90%
of the robot.

00:18:48.330 --> 00:18:52.080 align:middle line:84%
Later, it was determined that
the Martian soil is alkaline,

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:55.050 align:middle line:84%
with a pH of between
eight and nine.

00:18:55.050 --> 00:18:58.050 align:middle line:84%
And was analogous to the
soil of the nearby surface

00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:01.680 align:middle line:84%
in the valleys of
Antarctica on Earth.

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:04.530 align:middle line:84%
On September 30,
2008, the Phoenix

00:19:04.530 --> 00:19:07.540 align:middle line:84%
detected snow in the
atmosphere of Mars,

00:19:07.540 --> 00:19:10.590 align:middle line:84%
which was an
unprecedented observation.

00:19:10.590 --> 00:19:12.840 align:middle line:84%
A laser instrument
designed to analyze

00:19:12.840 --> 00:19:15.180 align:middle line:84%
interactions between
the atmosphere

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:17.280 align:middle line:84%
and the surface of
the Martian soil

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:23.040 align:middle line:84%
detected snow from clouds at
4,000 meters above Phoenix.

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:25.350 align:middle line:84%
According to the
observations, the snowflakes

00:19:25.350 --> 00:19:29.610 align:middle line:84%
turned into gas before
reaching the surface of Mars.

00:19:29.610 --> 00:19:32.310 align:middle line:84%
Experiments conducted
with Phoenix instruments

00:19:32.310 --> 00:19:36.270 align:middle line:84%
also revealed traces of chemical
reactions between minerals

00:19:36.270 --> 00:19:39.840 align:middle line:84%
from the Martian soil
and liquid water,

00:19:39.840 --> 00:19:43.080 align:middle line:84%
indicating periods in
Mars historical past

00:19:43.080 --> 00:19:46.410 align:middle line:90%
that water ran on the surface.

00:19:46.410 --> 00:19:48.750 align:middle line:84%
The data generated
by the Phoenix probes

00:19:48.750 --> 00:19:51.150 align:middle line:84%
also suggests the
presence of calcium

00:19:51.150 --> 00:19:55.290 align:middle line:84%
carbonate, the main
component of limestone.

00:19:55.290 --> 00:19:57.780 align:middle line:84%
Most carbonates
and clays on Earth

00:19:57.780 --> 00:20:00.990 align:middle line:84%
are formed in the
presence of water.

00:20:00.990 --> 00:20:03.720 align:middle line:84%
The analysis of
some images and data

00:20:03.720 --> 00:20:07.380 align:middle line:84%
show what appeared to be drops
of liquid saline water that

00:20:07.380 --> 00:20:10.830 align:middle line:84%
splashed the legs of
the probe after landing.

00:20:10.830 --> 00:20:14.790 align:middle line:84%
The climate on Mars is more
extreme than that on Earth.

00:20:14.790 --> 00:20:17.190 align:middle line:10%
And given that it is
farther from the sun,

00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:20.430 align:middle line:10%
the cold is more intense,
with an average temperature

00:20:20.430 --> 00:20:23.730 align:middle line:10%
of minus 63 degrees Celsius.

00:20:23.730 --> 00:20:28.170 align:middle line:10%
Although it can descend to 80
degrees below zero Celsius.

00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:29.910 align:middle line:84%
However, during the
day, the temperature

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:33.040 align:middle line:90%
can reach 20 degrees Celsius.

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:36.030 align:middle line:10%
The temperature at the Mars
two poles during the winter

00:20:36.030 --> 00:20:39.990 align:middle line:10%
can drop to 140
degrees below zero.

00:20:39.990 --> 00:20:43.440 align:middle line:84%
And in the summer, it can
exceed 30 degrees centigrade

00:20:43.440 --> 00:20:46.600 align:middle line:90%
or 86 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:20:46.600 --> 00:20:50.210 align:middle line:10%
It is possible that Mars
could be a habitable planet.

00:20:50.210 --> 00:20:52.560 align:middle line:10%
Its temperatures are
lower than on Earth,

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:55.830 align:middle line:10%
but not enough to consider that
life could not exist there.

00:20:55.830 --> 00:20:59.500 align:middle line:90%


00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:03.040 align:middle line:84%
The device that you see
here is called MOXIE.

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:06.520 align:middle line:84%
MOXIE is being designed to
use the electricity generated

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:11.470 align:middle line:84%
by a separate machine to convert
carbon monoxide to oxygen.

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:15.490 align:middle line:84%
Mars' atmosphere has the
presence of 96% oxygen

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:17.620 align:middle line:90%
and carbon monoxide.

00:21:17.620 --> 00:21:22.210 align:middle line:84%
The goal is to build a 100 scale
MOXIE so then in the 2030s,

00:21:22.210 --> 00:21:25.060 align:middle line:84%
it could produce liquid
oxygen for tanks.

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:27.130 align:middle line:84%
The purpose of these
liquid oxygen tanks

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:29.800 align:middle line:84%
would be to store fuel
so that astronauts could

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:33.790 align:middle line:84%
breathe oxygen. And be able
to return to Earth from Mars.

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:36.130 align:middle line:84%
It has been determined
that MOXIE could operate

00:21:36.130 --> 00:21:40.420 align:middle line:84%
for a period of 50 Martian days,
equivalent to about 51 Earth

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:44.530 align:middle line:84%
days, producing about 20
grams of oxygen per hour.

00:21:44.530 --> 00:21:46.660 align:middle line:84%
With the extended
version of the device,

00:21:46.660 --> 00:21:50.980 align:middle line:84%
it is expected to produce about
2 kilograms of oxygen per hour.

00:21:50.980 --> 00:21:53.530 align:middle line:84%
The MOXIE device would
be a necessary piece

00:21:53.530 --> 00:21:55.090 align:middle line:90%
of Mars equipment.

00:21:55.090 --> 00:21:59.900 align:middle line:90%


00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:03.440 align:middle line:84%
>> This means that there
are great possibilities

00:22:03.440 --> 00:22:07.040 align:middle line:84%
for the existence of
human life on Mars.

